IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos—Lagarde said she is open to serving another five years as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay on.
The International Monetary Fund has never had a better leader, and the IMF Board should give her the chance to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, assuming leadership of a troubled institution.
The global financial crisis of 2008 and its economic aftermath tarnished the reputation of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's reputation.
Many eyes were on her personal qualities — as they should be.
She is candid, strong, warm, and touching.
Foreign officials who met with her (often in delicate settings) frequently noted that she has the courage to speak the difficult truths while also being a sensitive listener.
For an institution leader who must negotiate agreement terms rather than dominate, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, otherwise firewalls had to be built to prevent financial contagion. Tough advice, but the Europeans followed it anyway.
Similarly, she advocated loudly for IMF support for countries like Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine, which was crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not particularly known for innovation and is usually not overly enthusiastic.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which is often prescriptive, a human face.
For example, managing the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally part of the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the Syrian and Iraqi conflicts (over one million people are living in camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to provide debt relief to affected countries, enabling them to improve the pay of doctors and nurses—this was the first time the IMF had used its capital in such a manner.
In addition, Lagarde recognized three of the most important challenges facing the world today and took action against them.
First, she strongly advocated for more women to join the workforce, setting an example as a leader herself.
She urged leaders across diverse nations from Saudi Arabia to Japan to stop wasting such enormous human resources—and thereby realize economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF research underscores the direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its standing makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has consistently advocated for this, which has been crucial in raising its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played a significant role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological changes — some of which will have frighteningly destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to enhance manufacturing efficiency and reduce costs, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be fewer than before.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF central to this work.
Critics might argue that it is time for developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is already the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's privilege in holding such a position is becoming increasingly hard to justify in today's world.
Some might argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded the desired results, indicating that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some might also point out that she faces allegations involving financial scandals in France, which could distract her from her work at the IMF.
After Dominique Strauss-Kahn's scandal, her critics argued that the IMF must not be distracted again by similar events.
Let's analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from beyond Europe and the United States.
But the aim of ending this Western privilege is to base the selection of leaders on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for IMF director, with emerging powers like the BRICs (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) not jointly putting forward an alternative.
It may have been one of the favorable factors for a European to lead the IMF last year when it decided to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies determining the value of its special drawing rights.
Moreover, Lagarde's impressive political flexibility ultimately convinced both Republicans and Democrats in the US Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal to combat financial crises but also more accurately reflected the dynamics of the evolving global economy.
For example, now the BRICs have joined the IMF's top ten shareholders.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde offered some personally colored candid comments last year—some saw them as inappropriate.
But she was certainly not the one to inflict economic pain on the Greeks; her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that no president in the history of the IMF has done as much to lead the institution in alleviating the suffering of people in crises.
Finally, France's charges against Lagarde were opposed by the French Chief Prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only tangentially involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has shown that she is such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF to the 21st century.
She should be given the opportunity to see it through.
